Maureen Ihua-Maduenyi The Lagos State Governor, Babajide Sanwo-Olu and the Chairman, Senate Committee on Judiciary, Human Rights and Legal Matters, Senator Opeyemi Bamidele, have said that innovative technologies would help the state and the country in general to effectively manage waste. Speaking at the 2019 World Habitat Day on Monday, Sanwo-Olu said effective waste management had become a priority globally, with technology as the key to sustainable development. The governor, who was represented by his deputy, Dr Obafemi Hamzat, also stated that it had become important to view waste as a valuable resource that could be turned to wealth through technology. He said, “This innovative approach will address all areas of the waste heirarchy from reduction to reuse, recycling, recovery and disposal. With innovation technology waste management system, cities can resolve not only the challenges, but also create employment and promote economic growth. “In line with our determination and commitment to ensure a cleaner and healthier environment, we have re-energised the solid waste management sector by promoting the concept of reduce, reuse and recycle as the major thrust of waste management in the state.” Bamidele stated that given growing global concerns for the creation of decent, stable and hygienic livelihood, it had become imperative for the government and other stakeholders to partner and encourage the invention of technologies to transform waste to wealth. Copyright PUNCH.
